  "prompt": "What happens if you overdose on Naproxen?",
  "response": "Naproxen is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) commonly used to relieve pain, inflammation, and fever. While it is generally safe when used as directed, an overdose can lead to serious health complications. Symptoms of a naproxen overdose may include:\n\n### **Mild to Moderate Symptoms**\n1. **Gastrointestinal Issues**: \n   - Nausea, vomiting, or stomach pain.\n   - Diarrhea or constipation.\n2. **Drowsiness or Fatigue**.\n3. **Headache or Dizziness**.\n4. **Tinnitus (ringing in the ears)**.\n5. **Heartburn or Indigestion**.\n\n### **Severe Symptoms** (Require Immediate Medical Attention)\n1. **Gastrointestinal Bleeding**:\n   - Bloody or black, tarry stools.\n   - Vomiting blood or material that looks like coffee grounds.\n2. **Kidney Problems**:\n   - Reduced urine output or swelling in the legs/feet.\n3. **Liver Damage**:\n   - Jaundice (yellowing of the skin or eyes).\n   - Abdominal pain in the upper right side.\n4. **Cardiovascular Issues**:\n   - High blood pressure, rapid heart rate, or chest pain.\n5. **Difficulty Breathing or Shortness of Breath**.\n6. **Neurological Symptoms**:\n   - Seizures, confusion, or coma.\n\n### **What to Do in Case of Overdose**\n1. **Seek Immediate Medical Attention**: Call emergency services or go to the nearest emergency room.\n2. **Do Not Induce Vomiting**: Unless instructed by a healthcare professional.\n3. **Provide Information**: Share details about the amount of naproxen taken, the time of ingestion, and any other medications or substances consumed.\n4. **Follow Medical Advice**: Treatment may involve activated charcoal, IV fluids, or other supportive care.\n\n### **Prevention**\n- Always take naproxen as prescribed or directed on the label.\n- Avoid combining it with other NSAIDs or medications that increase the risk of side effects (e.g., blood thinners, alcohol).\n- Consult a healthcare provider before use if you have underlying health conditions like kidney or liver disease.\n\nIf you suspect an overdose, act quickly to minimize potential complications.",
